EM5004_00_0.name: Dung Beetle
EM5004_00_0.explain: Insects that habitually roll up monster dung. The dung pods are well compacted and can be used as Slinger ammo.
EM5004_00_0.memo: Insects that habitually roll up monster dung. They bring it back to their underground nests not just for food, but to lay eggs on and feed their larvae. They're the faces of feces across the land: nature's diligent decomposers. The compacted dung pods formed by their efforts can be used as Slinger ammo. It's foul enough to send even large monsters running for fresh air—a useful trick when you're outnumbered.

EM5200_00_0.name: Windrustler
EM5200_00_0.explain: Herding monsters that mostly inhabit the savannah. They use their distinctive arrow-shaped crests to communicate and warn other members of their herd of danger.
EM5200_00_0.memo: Plains dwellers that move in packs. They use their arrow-like crests to coordinate movements and alert each other to threats. EM5201_00_0.name: Nothpecker

EM5202_00_0.name: Landlight Shrimp
EM5202_00_0.explain: A decomposer that breaks down the Fulgurite in its body consumed in order to eat the attached microbes. The Fulgurite makes its carapace shine.
EM5202_00_0.memo: Shrimp-like creatures that use their secretions to comb through fulgurite and feed on organic matter like dead Thunderbugs. EM5203_00_0.name: Amstrigian
EM5203_00_0.explain: A migratory bird that flocks to the savannah during the bounty season to raise its young. It makes its nest largely from the bubbles it produces internally.
EM5203_00_0.memo: Migrant birds that live in the forest, but travel to the plains during the Plenty to raise their young. Amstrigians choose lifelong mates and share the work when it comes to gathering food, building nests, and minding their young. Their meal of choice is insects, particularly Emperor Hoppers. They use their syrinxes to sing in chorus at the turning of the season, a social ritual that doubles as a form of communication.

EM5204_00_0.name: Rufflizard
EM5204_00_0.explain: A lizard that stores nutrients in a handkerchief-like sac. During the bounty season, it becomes predatorily active and its body takes on a red color.
EM5204_00_0.memo: Lizards with adipose tissue near their jaws and tail. When food is plentiful, these sac-like reservoirs fatten up and turn a healthy red. A Rufflizard with plenty of food in the tank is a happy Rufflizard, and you may see them basking in the sun and bobbing to each other in greeting. A poorly fed Rufflizard however, will move as little as possible.

EM5206_00_0.name: Tracktail Lizard
EM5206_00_0.explain: An animal distinctive for the monogamous pairing it forms with another individual of its species. It can use its large tail to stand itself up and warn others.
EM5206_00_0.memo: Endemic creatures that are native to the Windward Plains—particularly its deserts. EM5207_00_0.name: Emperor Hopper
EM5207_00_0.explain: A grasshopper as big as its moniker would suggest. Its swift, frenetic jumps make it hard to capture.
EM5207_00_0.memo: Huge grasshoppers that have fully earned their name. Their powerful hind legs allow them to jump long distances and escape in a pinch. If you rustle through the grass—their usual hiding spot—you're bound to see at least one Emperor Hopper spring away. Grass fires throw them into a panic, a situation that certain other hungry creatures might be eager to take advantage of.

memo_langs.Thai: แมลงบินที่มีลักษณะคล้ายโคลเวอร์สี่ใบ ทนทานต่อสภาพอากาศใด ๆ พวกมันสามารถพบได้ทั้งกลางวันและกลางคืนในเกือบทุกสภาพภูมิอากาศที่สัตว์ประหลาดไม่คาดว่าจะออกล่า ซึ่งเป็นสัญญาณที่ดีว่า บริเวณนั้นปลอดภัยพอสำหรับค่ายชั่วคราว

EM5217_00_0.name: Smokeshroud Gekko
EM5217_00_0.memo: Lizards with luminous organs around their body. When attacked, they go dark and leave luminous material in their wake as a decoy while they make a quick getaway. From this observation, it can be surmised that it's not their epidermis that glows, but some other substance stored in their bodies. In line with these habits, Smokeshroud Gekkos can generally be found in dark, gloomy places.

EM5219_00_0.name: Sandstar

Highly vigilant, they use their excellent hearing to detect approaching threats and flee, so trying to chase one down is the wrong approach. You'll have a far easier time catching one if you use a sonic bomb to disrupt its hearing.

EM5001_00_0.name: Paratoad

EM5001_00_0.memo: Toads containing a paralytic gas that are usually found by the water. Hunters can use this behavior to direct the gas at a desired target and gain the upper hand.

EM5007_00_0.name: Dark Hornet
EM5007_00_0.explain: Nocturnal hornets that use a luminous organ to warn foes before attacking with their stingers— even large monsters aren't safe.
EM5007_00_0.memo: Nocturnal hornets with strong defensive instincts. When they sense danger, they use a luminous organ to illuminate the area to check for threats, if one is spotted, they attack relentlessly with their poisonous stingers. Unlike other endemic life, Dark Hornets will readily attack large monsters that disturb their nests. Their diet also doesn't stimulate honey production, so hunters are better off steering clear.

EM5009_00_0.name: Wedge Beetle
EM5009_00_0.explain: Insects that cling firmly to walls and other surfaces. Latching on to them with the Slinger can help you traverse terrain and evade attacks.

EM5101_00_0.memo: Insects that emit strong bursts of light in response to external factors. It was long believed that blunt trauma or death were the triggers, but this theory has been rejected. In any case, their materials are highly prized for their utility in items like Slinger flash pods.

EM5101_20_0.name: Bitterbug
EM5101_20_0.explain: Insects whose bitter extracts promote natural healing and can be combined into a variety of useful medicines and items.
EM5101_20_0.memo: Insects whose bitter extracts are used for a wide variety of medicinal purposes. In addition to promoting natural healing, disinfecting, and mitigating poisons, they also boost the efficacy of other medicines, making them highly useful. EM5216_09_0.name: Curioshell Crab

They flee at full speed the instant they spot a foe, not bothering to camouflage themselves. Instead, they heap metal objects onto their carapaces, which are thought to be artifacts from ancient civilizations.

EM5210_00_0.name: Myriads
EM5210_00_0.memo: Butterflies that hatch during the Plenty and pupate near its close. Those that survive the harsh Fallow emerge during the following season of Plenty. They adapt their life cycle to the Scarlet Forest, so if a population hatches early, it may reach adulthood within the same season. They feed a variety of organisms, including insectivorous plants, making them a crucial, non-predatory part of the ecosystem.

EM5212_00_0.name: Vaporonid
EM5212_00_0.memo: Master weavers that use webs to ensnare prey. You will often see butterflies and other insects caught in their webs, which is as big as a person and is equipped with an escape route for the Vaporonid in case predators approach. The silk used in the web is extremely sturdy and comes in handy if you need to make pitfall traps to ensnare a few monsters of your own.

EM5213_00_0.name: Omenfly
EM5213_00_0.memo: Insects whose bellies glow yellow or red when they detect threats. Their resemblance to fossils seems to suggest that Omenflies have been around for quite a long time. The glowing seems to be a warning to enemies. Since Omenflies stay near the water, it is believed they keep their larvae in the water or in the moist soil nearby. Adults will stay airborne for the majority of their lives.

EM5214_00_0.name: Mimiphyta
EM5214_00_0.memo: Forest creatures that survive by using mimicry to disguise themselves as plants, confusing predators and luring in prey. Mimiphyta change form in response to seasonal and environmental changes; during the Fallow, they'll snuggle up at the base of a tree to live as fungi, while in the season of Plenty they blossom into lovely flowers and prey on butterflies and insects that flutter near.

EM5215_00_0.name: Scarlet Joyperch
EM5215_00_0.memo: Creatures that have adapted to living both on land and in the water. They are precious evidence of how amphibious creatures might have come to walk the earth. Scarlet Joyperch become active at night, when they light up the luminous organs near their heads, spread their fins, and let out a cry— presumably their way of strutting their stuff to other members of their kind.

EM5216_00_0.name: Florashell Crab
EM5216_00_0.memo: Crabs that pile plants on their cup-like carapaces and burrow into the ground to hide from predators. Their claws are shaped like shovels, allowing them to burrow more easily. They generally remain buried during the day, becoming active only at night, where they can be found digging for insects to eat.

EM5218_00_0.name: Dapperwing
EM5218_00_0.memo: A species noted for its males, who don spectacularly colorful plumage after molting. During the Fallow, their plumage is a subdued green to match the vegetation, but once the Plenty arrives, males preen to the nines, adopting a vibrant color palette— presumably to court females, since the more flamboyant males with larger feathers seem to be the ones flapping away with a date.

EM5218_09_0.name: Dazzlewing

EM5220_00_0.name: Scalebat
EM5220_00_0.memo: Creatures that greatly resemble bats. They hang from the ceiling in dark places like caves, and become active at night, preying on insects and smaller flying creatures. They can also be found in forests. Because of characteristics like their scales, it is theorized that they may have evolved from wyverns. Huge colonies live in caves in the Oilwell Basin, as evidenced by the piles of dung found there.

EM5300_00_0.name: Starduster
EM5300_00_0.explain: A small fish that moves in large schools. It is common in bodies of water of the Windward Plains and the Forest. Notable for its bright, reflective blue and gold scales.
EM5300_00_0.memo: Small fish with blue and yellow scales that prefer to live in schools. The sizes of these schools vary and at times can become impressively large. Because they both breed rapidly and exist in large numbers, they are frequently preyed upon, making them the backbone of the ecosystem. Splashes on the surface of bodies of water are a sign of this fish fleeing from large predators.

memo_langs.English: Small fish with blue and yellow scales that prefer to live in schools. The sizes of these schools vary and at times can become impressively large. Because they both breed rapidly and exist in large numbers, they are frequently preyed upon, making them the backbone of the ecosystem. Splashes on the surface of bodies of water are a sign of this fish fleeing from large predators.
memo_langs.Thai: ปลาเล็กที่มีเกล็ดสีฟ้าและเหลืองที่ชอบอยู่เป็นฝูง ขนาดของฝูงเหล่านี้แตกต่างกันและบางครั้งอาจใหญ่โตอย่างน่าทึ่ง เนื่องจากพวกมันสืบพันธุ์อย่างรวดเร็วและมีจำนวนมากจึงมักถูกล่า ทำให้พวกมันเป็นกระดูกสันหลังของระบบนิเวศ รอยกระเซ็นบนผิวน้ำเป็นสัญญาณว่าปลานี้กำลังหนีจากนักล่าใหญ่

EM5313_00_0.name: Petricanths
EM5313_00_0.memo: So few of these fish have been found alive that they were once thought to be extinct. At one point, they only turned up as fossils —and in a way, they <ITALIC>are</ITALIC> living fossils since they retain the same form as in ancient times. Research on the ecology of the Petricanths might just elucidate how other prehistoric organisms lived. Petricanths show a strong interest in Duster Rigs.

EM5202_10_0.name: Pink Landlight Shrimp
EM5202_10_0.memo: Land-dwelling crustaceans that gather on gaseous vents in the Oilwell Basin. The hair on their heads and chests collects particles from the gas and steam, which attract the microbes that they feed on. EM5204_10_0.name: Ember Rufflizard
EM5204_10_0.memo: Lizards with distinctive creases on their heads. When they bob their heads to communicate, the crease opens and glows along with the pattern on their bodies. They prefer hot environments such as volcanic areas. Though rarely seen in the oilsilt- filled upper areas of the Oilwell Basin, they become far more active during the Firespring. It's theorized that they primarily feed on bugs that lurk among the rocks.

EM5216_10_0.name: Crudeshell Crab
EM5216_10_0.memo: Crabs that pile oilsilt on their cup-like carapaces and burrow into the ground to hide from predators. Because oilsilt itself changes appearance depending on the season, it's theorized that these crabs must replace their silt to match. They are rarely seen in volcanic regions or during the Firespring, suggesting that they aren't particularly resistant to heat.

Populations have been observed living in some human settlements, allowing their eggs to be gathered in an extremely unusual symbiotic relationship.
memo_langs.Thai: นกที่สามารถเห็นขี่บนหลังสัตว์ประหลาดตัวเล็ก พวกมันระมัดระวังภัยคุกคามภายนอกอย่างยิ่งและรีบหนี ทำให้จับได้ยาก ขาที่ยาวผิดสัดส่วนช่วยให้พวกมันเคลื่อนที่ด้วยความเร็วสูง มีการสังเกตว่าพวกมันอาศัยอยู่ในบางชุมชนมนุษย์ ทำให้ไข่ของพวกมันถูกเก็บไว้ในความสัมพันธ์พึ่งพาอาศัยที่แปลกประหลาดอย่างยิ่ง

EM5004_20_0.name: Rime Beetle
EM5004_20_0.explain: Beetles that gather up snowballs and roll them back to their nests. The snowballs can be used as Slinger frostburst ammo.
EM5004_20_0.memo: Beetles that gather up snow. Their snowballs can be used as Frostburst Ammo. Due to their ecology, Icebeetles are limited to cold habitats and are more tolerant of cold than other insects. No one knows why they roll their snowballs back to their nests. Some theorize it's to grow the organic matter they feed on, while others think it could be related to reproductive behavior.

EM5005_20_0.name: Heatmantle Bug
EM5005_20_0.explain: Insects that hoard honey with cold-relieving properties in the casing on their backs. They ferment plants with heating components.
EM5005_20_0.memo: Insects that live in extremely cold environments. They wrap themselves in plant matter—much like their mantle bug brethren—but they use plants with heating properties, such as hot peppers, to mitigate the cold. They can live on the surface thanks to this, but if uncloaked they must burrow underground to survive.

EM5207_10_0.name: Tyrant Hopper
EM5207_10_0.memo: A phase mutation of the Emperor Hopper. Their bodies are reddish-black and are more ferocious. While Hoppers are usually herbivorous, this type feeds on carrion. Due to similarities across different regions, it is believed the mutation must occur in environments where plants are scarce. This causal relationship between a creature's formative environment and its mutations has become a major subject of research.

EM5222_10_0.name: Xu Yo
EM5222_10_0.memo: Xu Wu larvae, newly hatched from their eggs. They already give off a faint luminescence, and patterns can be seen through their thin, transparent skin. They generally move in groups, but not in an organized manner— it's only because they hatched at the same time. After hatching, the nutrients from their eggs sustain them for a while. Beyond that, their diet remains unknown.

EM5225_00_0.name: Petalfly
EM5225_00_0.memo: Insects found in areas with ample vegetation such as the heart of the Ruins of Wyveria. Petalflies have poor flight capabilities, but they can still use the wind to get around. The larvae live in water or on moist ground until they mature, while an adult's short life span is spent reproducing. It has been suggested that the flowery fragrance the Petalflies give off may be a pheromone linked to mating.

EM5208_20_0.name: Prism Hercudrome
EM5208_20_0.memo: A member of the Hercudrome family with an iridescent carapace. Its pronotum is large and developed, with three prominent horns. Unlike ordinary Hercudromes, these inhabit the Ruins of Wyveria. Alas, there have been precious few sightings. Most have been at dawn or dusk, so that might be the best time to attempt and capture one.
